Ideally, there should be a separate interface for each `type`, as the shape looks different. Optional properties don't make much sense in this case, as they are specific only to a subset of `type`s. If there is a need for a base/common type you can have a union type, with `type` as discriminant. E.g.:
```ts
interface HotNotifierInfoDeclined {
    type: "declined";
    chain: number[];
    //...
}
interface HotNotifierInfoAccepted {
    type: "accepted";
    outdatedModules: number[];
    // ...
}
type HotNotifierInfo = HotNotifierInfoDeclined | HotNotifierinfoAccepted | ....;
```

